$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_DATA_TEXT." (page_id, field_id, value, search_value) VALUES (22, 15, '<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\"><span style=\\\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(148, 28, 27); background: transparent;\\\"><strong style=\\\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: transparent;\\\">2000 onwards:</strong></span>&nbsp;i.e., the second tenure of Fr Varghese Anikuzhy S.J. as the Principal, may be treated as a single unit in the history of the school. This period not only witnessed infrastructure development on a gigantic scale and at a brisk pace, but also reaffirmed and improved upon the legacy of all-round excellence.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">The major additions and alterations to the infrastructure during this period are:</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">The first two floors of the CBSE wing, networking facility in the computer lab, Loyola Cricket Academy and fully equipped multimedia room open to all classes&mdash;all in 2002;&nbsp; the Children&rsquo;s Park in 2003; the third floor of the CBSE block and five new science labs and a&nbsp; language lab there in 2007; the gigantic Indoor Stadium and the facelift to the main gate in 2009, asphalting all roads on the campus and concreting the basketball court on the Northern side in 2010; roofing and floor-tiling of the canteen-lounge-cum-waiting shed, the new RCC retention wall along the the boundary on the stadium end, and five more buses that increased the fleet-strength to eleven&mdash;all in 2011; CCTV surveillance of the entire campus and the electronic display facility for daily news flash in 2012&mdash;all of these at the cost of a few crores.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">Among the many Loyolites who distinguished themselves at the national and state levels during this period are: Jayendran S., Jian Johnson, Anoop Sankar, Thaseem T. and Rex Thomas who won the Hindu Young World and India Cultural Quiz at the national level and ISC and ICSE quizzes at the state level in 2001 (the Jayendran-Jian team finishing as runner up in the Hindu Young World Quiz in 2002 and again in 2003); Jayakrishnan who secured the first rank in Kerala Engineering Entrance exam in 2001; Varun Murali and Jayendran S. who were the national runner-up in the prestigious ESPN Sports Quiz at Delhi in 2002; Kishor Govind Nayar, Ashique Siyad, Hari Sankar V., Avinesh Vasudevan, Mishel Johns, and Sriram P. who won the first National Aerospace Olympiad in 2007; Vineeth Krishnan and Vishnu M.J. who stood first in the National ISC Quiz in 2007, Aju Basil James who teamed up with Leo Francis to lift the National ICSE quiz trophy in 2007; Achuth Vasudevan and Aju Basil James who were the national champions in Aqua Regia Quiz at Hyderabad in 2007, Arjun Shajan and Rahul Krishnan who were the runner-up in the ICSE National Junior quiz in 2007; Yadhu Aravind Menon who won the Sastra Prathibha award in 2007, Paul Mathew T. who was the national first in the 7th Cyber Olympiad in 2009, Dany John Selvan who won the national championship in Fencing in 2006 and Sandeep Prakash who got into the national school cricket team the same year, and a good number of K.V.P.Y and NTS scholars and many quiz wizards who brought home to Loyola a large number of trophies.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">On the academic front, the results of the Board exams continued to be enviable throughout the first decade of this century &mdash; producing seven state-level rank holders in just two years&mdash; Kishor Govind Nayar and Manoj P. sharing the first rank in ISC Science and Gokul Suresh and Nidhin R. coming second and third, respectively, in the ICSE exam of 2009; Ben Thomas and Kiran George Koshy securing the first and second rank, respectively, in the ISC exam in 2010 and Ambareesh S.J. coming second in the ICSE exam in 2010.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">In the arena of sports and games too, the period has memorable achievements. In 2003, 26 students of Loyola played in the tournament conducted by MCC Club Colombo, Sri Lanka, and the U-19 and U-14 teams won</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">four out of eight one-dayers there. The same year, the school hosted the 21st All Kerala ICSE/ISC Sports Meet in September at the University Stadium, and on the invitation of the YMCA Cricket Academy of Bangalore the school team played in the Peace Cup 2003 and the Juniors won the cup and three seniors distinguished themselves&mdash;Anoop Krishnan (Best Batsman), Arun Datt Pullat (Best All-rounder) and Arun K. (Best Bowler). Loyola U-18 team played against Bangladesh, England and a Delhi team in the Delhi Public School World Cup Tournament and won against the Delhi team. The U-13 and U-18 teams won the Lal Bahadur Shastri Cricket Tournament conducted by the Sports Authority of Goa and Ajith John was declared the Best Batsman of the tournament. In May 2004, Loyola Cricket Academy students left for Sri Lanka and won all the games they played there and in the first test, Likhin Francis was adjudged the Man of the Match; Shekhar, the Best Bowler; Ali Asgar, the Best Batsman; and in the second test Pradyoth Nandak won the Man of the Match award. In August 2004 Loyola Cricket Academy hosted an International Cricket tournament at Trivandrum and reached the final which they lost to Goa. In 2009 Loyola team won the Jaihind Trophy in cricket and Jithin R. won the Man of the Match honour. Varun Sujith Nair won the individual championship in the ICSE swimming competition in 2009 and the next year he set a Record in 100 mts Butterfly Stroke in the ICSE Aquatic Meet, Kerala.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">Among the major changes during this period are: increasing the student-intake by gradually adding one more division to each class (which has resulted in almost doubling the student-strength from 900 in 1980 to about 1750 in 2012); starting the CBSE and HSE stream in 2002; the upgradation of the CBSE stream to the Senior Secondary level in 2008 and the experimental introduction of the Humanities section to theISC stream in 2010.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">Among other memorable events and achievements of the period are: &#39;Back to School&#39; becoming an unfailing annual programme, three senior Loyolites (Prasanth N., Vyasan R. and Anish Rajan) finding themselves among the Top 10 in the IAS Examination of 2007, the Fifth National Jesuit Alumni Congress on Loyola Campus in September 2007and Dr A.P.J.Abdul Kalam&#39;s visit on 24 July 2009.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p style=\\\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif; text-align: justify; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;\\\">The year 2011 remains unforgettable for the grand celebration of the Golden Jubilee which formally began on 4 June and ended with the publication of the Souvenir on 26 November and with many colourful programmes like a the Musical Night by renowned playback singers and a three-day Carnival on a grand scale thrown in between.</p>\\r\\n', '2000 onwards: i.e., the second tenure of Fr Varghese Anikuzhy S.J. as the Principal, may be treated as a single unit in the history of the school. This period not only witnessed infrastructure development on a gigantic scale and at a brisk pace, but also reaffirmed and improved upon the legacy of all-round excellence. The major additions and alterations to the infrastructure during this period are: The first two floors of the CBSE wing, networking facility in the computer lab, Loyola Cricket Academy and fully equipped multimedia room open to all classes—all in 2002;  the Children’s Park in 2003; the third floor of the CBSE block and five new science labs and a  language lab there in 2007; the gigantic Indoor Stadium and the facelift to the main gate in 2009, asphalting all roads on the campus and concreting the basketball court on the Northern side in 2010; roofing and floor-tiling of the canteen-lounge-cum-waiting shed, the new RCC retention wall along the the boundary on the stadium end, and five more buses that increased the fleet-strength to eleven—all in 2011; CCTV surveillance of the entire campus and the electronic display facility for daily news flash in 2012—all of these at the cost of a few crores. Among the many Loyolites who distinguished themselves at the national and state levels during this period are: Jayendran S., Jian Johnson, Anoop Sankar, Thaseem T. and Rex Thomas who won the Hindu Young World and India Cultural Quiz at the national level and ISC and ICSE quizzes at the state level in 2001 (the Jayendran-Jian team finishing as runner up in the Hindu Young World Quiz in 2002 and again in 2003); Jayakrishnan who secured the first rank in Kerala Engineering Entrance exam in 2001; Varun Murali and Jayendran S. who were the national runner-up in the prestigious ESPN Sports Quiz at Delhi in 2002; Kishor Govind Nayar, Ashique Siyad, Hari Sankar V., Avinesh Vasudevan, Mishel Johns, and Sriram P. who won the first National Aerospace Olympiad in 2007; Vineeth Krishnan and Vishnu M.J. who stood first in the National ISC Quiz in 2007, Aju Basil James who teamed up with Leo Francis to lift the National ICSE quiz trophy in 2007; Achuth Vasudevan and Aju Basil James who were the national champions in Aqua Regia Quiz at Hyderabad in 2007, Arjun Shajan and Rahul Krishnan who were the runner-up in the ICSE National Junior quiz in 2007; Yadhu Aravind Menon who won the Sastra Prathibha award in 2007, Paul Mathew T. who was the national first in the 7th Cyber Olympiad in 2009, Dany John Selvan who won the national championship in Fencing in 2006 and Sandeep Prakash who got into the national school cricket team the same year, and a good number of K.V.P.Y and NTS scholars and many quiz wizards who brought home to Loyola a large number of trophies. On the academic front, the results of the Board exams continued to be enviable throughout the first decade of this century — producing seven state-level rank holders in just two years— Kishor Govind Nayar and Manoj P. sharing the first rank in ISC Science and Gokul Suresh and Nidhin R. coming second and third, respectively, in the ICSE exam of 2009; Ben Thomas and Kiran George Koshy securing the first and second rank, respectively, in the ISC exam in 2010 and Ambareesh S.J. coming second in the ICSE exam in 2010. In the arena of sports and games too, the period has memorable achievements. In 2003, 26 students of Loyola played in the tournament conducted by MCC Club Colombo, Sri Lanka, and the U-19 and U-14 teams won four out of eight one-dayers there. The same year, the school hosted the 21st All Kerala ICSE/ISC Sports Meet in September at the University Stadium, and on the invitation of the YMCA Cricket Academy of Bangalore the school team played in the Peace Cup 2003 and the Juniors won the cup and three seniors distinguished themselves—Anoop Krishnan (Best Batsman), Arun Datt Pullat (Best All-rounder) and Arun K. (Best Bowler). Loyola U-18 team played against Bangladesh, England and a Delhi team in the Delhi Public School World Cup Tournament and won against the Delhi team. The U-13 and U-18 teams won the Lal Bahadur Shastri Cricket Tournament conducted by the Sports Authority of Goa and Ajith John was declared the Best Batsman of the tournament. In May 2004, Loyola Cricket Academy students left for Sri Lanka and won all the games they played there and in the first test, Likhin Francis was adjudged the Man of the Match; Shekhar, the Best Bowler; Ali Asgar, the Best Batsman; and in the second test Pradyoth Nandak won the Man of the Match award. In August 2004 Loyola Cricket Academy hosted an International Cricket tournament at Trivandrum and reached the final which they lost to Goa. In 2009 Loyola team won the Jaihind Trophy in cricket and Jithin R. won the Man of the Match honour. Varun Sujith Nair won the individual championship in the ICSE swimming competition in 2009 and the next year he set a Record in 100 mts Butterfly Stroke in the ICSE Aquatic Meet, Kerala. Among the major changes during this period are: increasing the student-intake by gradually adding one more division to each class (which has resulted in almost doubling the student-strength from 900 in 1980 to about 1750 in 2012); starting the CBSE and HSE stream in 2002; the upgradation of the CBSE stream to the Senior Secondary level in 2008 and the experimental introduction of the Humanities section to theISC stream in 2010. Among other memorable events and achievements of the period are: &#039;Back to School&#039; becoming an unfailing annual programme, three senior Loyolites (Prasanth N., Vyasan R. and Anish Rajan) finding themselves among the Top 10 in the IAS Examination of 2007, the Fifth National Jesuit Alumni Congress on Loyola Campus in September 2007and Dr A.P.J.Abdul Kalam&#039;s visit on 24 July 2009. The year 2011 remains unforgettable for the grand celebration of the Golden Jubilee which formally began on 4 June and ended with the publication of the Souvenir on 26 November and with many colourful programmes like a the Musical Night by renowned playback singers and a three-day Carnival on a grand scale thrown in between.');";
