$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (14, '1960-1964', '1960-1964 Milestones 1960: Establishment of the Kerala Jesuit Province on 27 September, with Rev. Fr. Joseph Edamaram S.J. as the first Provincial who shortly afterwards founded Loyola School and a college in Trivandrum, the latter of which got bifurcated into Loyola College of Social Sciences at Sreekaryam and St Xavier’s College at Thumba. 1961 June: Birth of Loyola School at a borrowed abode at Palayam with Fr. K.V. John S.J. as the first Principal and 36 students on the rolls. 1962: Temporary transplantation to the Monvila campus and the starting of a Boarding House there, with Fr. K.V. John S.J. followed by Fr. P.C. Antony S.J. at the helm as Principals. 1963: Permanent transplantation to the present campus, farewell to the Kerala syllabus, and the introduction of the ISC course with its Board in Delhi and affiliation to Cambridge University—all thanks to the dynamism of the third Principal, Fr Antony Vachaparambil S.J. who handed over the charge to Fr. Thomas Anthraper S.J. in June 1963. 1964 May: Fr John Kunjaparambil S.J. assumed office as the fifth Principal, introduced weekly assemblies and the offices of the School Captain and the General Secretary, divided the students into four Houses (Panthers, Leopards, Lions &amp; Tigers), and provided for more regular practice for the promotion of sports and games as well as leadership qualities. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (15, '1965-1970', '1965-1970 Milestones 1965-70: The Era of Fr. Kuncheria S.J. The first major phase of infrastructure development was presided over by the sixth Principal Fr Kuncheria Ettuparayil S.J. His tenure also witnessed vigorous activities in both curricular and co-curricular fields. He increased the student-strength to 400 [120 boarders+280 day scholars], bought two buses for the school, introduced the first emblem and brought out the first issue of  the School Annual The Loyolite, enlivened the Literary Association, and arranged special training in oratory and debate. 1966: Supported by the Rector, Fr. K.P. Joseph S.J., and assisted by the Vice- Principal, Fr Mathew Pulickal S.J.,  the blueprint of the main wing of the present ICSE block was prepared and the resource mobilisation was begun with a Benefit Show at Tagore Theatre on 15 October. 1967: The Jesuit General Rev. Fr Peter Arrupe S.J. laid the foundation stone of the ICSE Block on 17 January.  Fr.  Joseph Vattakunnel S.J. rendered yeoman service as the Builder and Curator.  The year saw student-strength shooting up to 550 and Boarding strength, to 150; the introduction of vernacular in lower classes and Youth Festival for the whole school and the beginning of  NCC Air Wing.  Other additions to the infrastructure include the third school bus, a small auditorium, movie projector, tennis court, hockey ground, ping pong tables, canteen, reading room, zoo, and instruments for the newly started Music Club A prominent visitor of the period was Rev. Fr John L. Swain S.J., the Assistant General of the Jesuit congregation. 1968: Bought 5.8 acres of contiguous land for further development. Presented the first ISC batch that started the tradition of 100% pass. 1970: Completed the construction of the front part of the three-storeyed ICSE block and carved out the main playground. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (16, '1971-1973', '1971-1973 Milestones 1971-73: In spite of the difficult patch that Fr A.E. Makil S.J. had to live through as the Principal during this period, he left his footprint on the campus by erecting a separate single-storeyed Junior School and the sports pavilion-cum- canteen complex—both in Laurie Baker style— and got Loyola recognized by the Central Government as the first boys’ school in Kerala for the placement of National Merit Scholars. An indication of the academic excellence of this period is the fact that 6 Loyolites of the 1972 batch got into the IIT. Also, it was during this time that an Evening School was started to give free tuition to the students of neighbouring schools. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (17, '1974-1975', '1974-1975 Milestones 1974: Fr. Maurice Stanford, a Canadian Jesuit of the Darjeeling Province, assumed office as the Principal, instituted the Loyola Annual Inter-school Basketball tournament, and divided the students into AP, JJ, GG and SS Houses. The year is unforgettable for Mother Theresa&#039;s visit. 1975: End of the 11-year ISC pattern and the introduction of ICSE exam for class X and the +2 system thereafter. Yet another year of bustling activities and memorable achievements—700 students participating in the Youth Festival, special coaching for football and cricket, five mini-basketballers making it to the state team, winning five out of six inter-school matches in football, basketball and cricket, and producing enviable results in the ISC exam. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (18, '1976-1983', '1976-1983 Milestones 1976-83: Fr. C.P. Varkey era: In the very first year of his assuming office as Principal, Fr C.P.Varkey S.J. revitalized the system of weekly tests, introduced weekly quiz programme for std. VI to VIII, provided for professional training for a total of 200 students in cricket, hockey and basketball, raised funds for 25 full or partial scholarships, paved the way for the birth of the bi-weekly newsletter LENS, added the SSLC curriculum, raised the bar of excellence by producing 5 out of 35 NTS scholars in Kerala and kept up the tradition of 100% first class pass in all board exams. And in the years that followed he improved upon the record in every field and brought in many more reforms too — like simplification of the school uniform, introduction of a number of service squads, ensuring that around 80 to 90% of students took part in the youth festival and around 75 students enjoyed fee concession and that the whole school was shown a film every fortnight. The major construction during his tenure was the Western wing of the ICSE block at the cost of a little over Rs. 17 lakhs. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (19, '1983-1987', '1983-1987 Milestones 1983-87: Fr Varghese Anikuzhy S.J’s first term as Principal, a period noted for all-round excellence. In the curricular field the tradition of 100% pass was bettered with 100% distinction in the SSLC exam of 1985 and an average of 35 students getting into professional colleges on merit every year. The construction of an additional basketball court with concrete floor and fibre-glass boards and disciplined coaching in hockey, cricket, roller skating, basketball and gymnastics helped as many as five students to get into the state team in 1986 and accounted for the recapturing of the Loyola basketball trophy after an interval of five years. Social service activities showed a preference for the neighbouring schools, helping them with books and uniform and arranging sports meets and other competitions for them. January 1987 was especially memorable for the fitting celebration of the Silver Jubilee with a number of inter-school cultural competitions and a two-day Arts and Science Exhibition involving a large number of Govt. departments and autonomous agencies and for bringing out the Jubilee Souvenir. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (20, '1987-1994', '1987-1994 Milestones 1987-94: The major infrastructure development of this period is the construction of the Southern wing of the ICSE block at a cost of Rs. 29 Lakhs in 1993 and the addition of a football court and the purchase of a new bus and the fencing of the school grounds. On the academic front, he initiated tentative computer training shortly after his assumption of office and later introduced the the ISC course, in 1993, and maintained the tradition of 100% pass and about 90% Distinction in all streams. Loyola’s position among the schools in India during this period is clear from the fact that in 1989 two students (Muralikrishnan and Vinod V. Menon) distinguished themselves in the ICSE exam by securing the IInd and IVth Rank, respectively— a feat repeated by R. Anand who was the national second in the ISC exam of 1994.  In the 1993 Singapore Airlines Scholarship examination, 3 out of 25 students in India were Loyolites.  In addition to a total of about 50 NTS scholars, a few other students with creditable achievements during this period are Chandrasekhar who emerged as the winner of the Indian National Maths Olympiad in 1994, Sam Idiculla, Mathew, and J. Sony who reached the final round of the National Computer Contest of IIT Madras in 1990. In sports and games the school scaled further heights and won the Youth Affairs and Sports Department’s prize money of Rs. 10,000 consecutively for two years and also produced a yearly average of three state-level players in as many as five different fields. Among the sportsmen with special achievements during this period are Tinu Thomas who won 5 Gold medals in XI Kerala Roller Skating championship in 1992 and Eapen T. Joseph who got into both the Junior State and State Schools teams in basketball. Quiz was another field where the school made an indelible mark, bringing home more than 35 trophies during this period. One of the most prominent visitors of this period was Rev. Fr Peter-Hans Kolvenback (Jesuit Superior General) in 1990. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (21, '1995-2000', '1995-2000 Milestones 1995-2000: Two Jesuits presided over the destinies of the school during the last quinquennium of the 20th centrury — Fr. Mani Manimala from 1994 to 1997 and Fr. Kuruvila Cherian from 1997 to 2000. Some of the highlights of this period are: the three-day Inter-School Science Exhibition in 1995, Vice-Principal Fr Mathew Pulickal’s retirement in 1996 after 13 years of service, starting of LAFest in 1997, excellent results in all Board exams which qualified the school for the M.V. Mathai Rolling Trophy in 1997, as many as 27 Loyolites getting into IITs and 19 winning NTS scholarship and almost all others securing merit-based admission to professional colleges and an yearly average of 4 sportsmen getting selected to State-level teams, Harisankar securing the first rank in INMO in 1995 and the second rank in 1996, Vijay Gopalan representing Kerala in the Inter-State quiz in Delhi in 1998,  Jayakrishnan winning the Sastra Prathibha award (2000) and Vishnu Dattan winning the All India essay competitin of The Hindu (2000), completion of the mini-stadium near the Junior School in 1997-98, purchase of an electronic organ and another school bus, installation of the dish antenna, replenishing of the library and renovation of labs and the toilets, construction of another basketball court and commissioning of a fully air-conditioned computer lab with 25 systems along with multimedia and UPS support at the cost of Rs.11 lakh in 2000, and the demolition of the Junior School to erect the present CBSE Block. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (22, '2000 onwards', '2000 onwards Milestones 2000 onwards: i.e., the second tenure of Fr Varghese Anikuzhy S.J. as the Principal, may be treated as a single unit in the history of the school. This period not only witnessed infrastructure development on a gigantic scale and at a brisk pace, but also reaffirmed and improved upon the legacy of all-round excellence. The major additions and alterations to the infrastructure during this period are: The first two floors of the CBSE wing, networking facility in the computer lab, Loyola Cricket Academy and fully equipped multimedia room open to all classes—all in 2002;  the Children’s Park in 2003; the third floor of the CBSE block and five new science labs and a  language lab there in 2007; the gigantic Indoor Stadium and the facelift to the main gate in 2009, asphalting all roads on the campus and concreting the basketball court on the Northern side in 2010; roofing and floor-tiling of the canteen-lounge-cum-waiting shed, the new RCC retention wall along the the boundary on the stadium end, and five more buses that increased the fleet-strength to eleven—all in 2011; CCTV surveillance of the entire campus and the electronic display facility for daily news flash in 2012—all of these at the cost of a few crores. Among the many Loyolites who distinguished themselves at the national and state levels during this period are: Jayendran S., Jian Johnson, Anoop Sankar, Thaseem T. and Rex Thomas who won the Hindu Young World and India Cultural Quiz at the national level and ISC and ICSE quizzes at the state level in 2001 (the Jayendran-Jian team finishing as runner up in the Hindu Young World Quiz in 2002 and again in 2003); Jayakrishnan who secured the first rank in Kerala Engineering Entrance exam in 2001; Varun Murali and Jayendran S. who were the national runner-up in the prestigious ESPN Sports Quiz at Delhi in 2002; Kishor Govind Nayar, Ashique Siyad, Hari Sankar V., Avinesh Vasudevan, Mishel Johns, and Sriram P. who won the first National Aerospace Olympiad in 2007; Vineeth Krishnan and Vishnu M.J. who stood first in the National ISC Quiz in 2007, Aju Basil James who teamed up with Leo Francis to lift the National ICSE quiz trophy in 2007; Achuth Vasudevan and Aju Basil James who were the national champions in Aqua Regia Quiz at Hyderabad in 2007, Arjun Shajan and Rahul Krishnan who were the runner-up in the ICSE National Junior quiz in 2007; Yadhu Aravind Menon who won the Sastra Prathibha award in 2007, Paul Mathew T. who was the national first in the 7th Cyber Olympiad in 2009, Dany John Selvan who won the national championship in Fencing in 2006 and Sandeep Prakash who got into the national school cricket team the same year, and a good number of K.V.P.Y and NTS scholars and many quiz wizards who brought home to Loyola a large number of trophies. On the academic front, the results of the Board exams continued to be enviable throughout the first decade of this century — producing seven state-level rank holders in just two years— Kishor Govind Nayar and Manoj P. sharing the first rank in ISC Science and Gokul Suresh and Nidhin R. coming second and third, respectively, in the ICSE exam of 2009; Ben Thomas and Kiran George Koshy securing the first and second rank, respectively, in the ISC exam in 2010 and Ambareesh S.J. coming second in the ICSE exam in 2010. In the arena of sports and games too, the period has memorable achievements. In 2003, 26 students of Loyola played in the tournament conducted by MCC Club Colombo, Sri Lanka, and the U-19 and U-14 teams won four out of eight one-dayers there. The same year, the school hosted the 21st All Kerala ICSE/ISC Sports Meet in September at the University Stadium, and on the invitation of the YMCA Cricket Academy of Bangalore the school team played in the Peace Cup 2003 and the Juniors won the cup and three seniors distinguished themselves—Anoop Krishnan (Best Batsman), Arun Datt Pullat (Best All-rounder) and Arun K. (Best Bowler). Loyola U-18 team played against Bangladesh, England and a Delhi team in the Delhi Public School World Cup Tournament and won against the Delhi team. The U-13 and U-18 teams won the Lal Bahadur Shastri Cricket Tournament conducted by the Sports Authority of Goa and Ajith John was declared the Best Batsman of the tournament. In May 2004, Loyola Cricket Academy students left for Sri Lanka and won all the games they played there and in the first test, Likhin Francis was adjudged the Man of the Match; Shekhar, the Best Bowler; Ali Asgar, the Best Batsman; and in the second test Pradyoth Nandak won the Man of the Match award. In August 2004 Loyola Cricket Academy hosted an International Cricket tournament at Trivandrum and reached the final which they lost to Goa. In 2009 Loyola team won the Jaihind Trophy in cricket and Jithin R. won the Man of the Match honour. Varun Sujith Nair won the individual championship in the ICSE swimming competition in 2009 and the next year he set a Record in 100 mts Butterfly Stroke in the ICSE Aquatic Meet, Kerala. Among the major changes during this period are: increasing the student-intake by gradually adding one more division to each class (which has resulted in almost doubling the student-strength from 900 in 1980 to about 1750 in 2012); starting the CBSE and HSE stream in 2002; the upgradation of the CBSE stream to the Senior Secondary level in 2008 and the experimental introduction of the Humanities section to theISC stream in 2010. Among other memorable events and achievements of the period are: &#039;Back to School&#039; becoming an unfailing annual programme, three senior Loyolites (Prasanth N., Vyasan R. and Anish Rajan) finding themselves among the Top 10 in the IAS Examination of 2007, the Fifth National Jesuit Alumni Congress on Loyola Campus in September 2007and Dr A.P.J.Abdul Kalam&#039;s visit on 24 July 2009. The year 2011 remains unforgettable for the grand celebration of the Golden Jubilee which formally began on 4 June and ended with the publication of the Souvenir on 26 November and with many colourful programmes like a the Musical Night by renowned playback singers and a three-day Carnival on a grand scale thrown in between. ');";
$k_stmts[] = "INSERT INTO ".K_TBL_FULLTEXT." (page_id, title, content) VALUES (23, 'Loyola Old Boys Association (LOBA)', 'LOBA Loyola Old Boys Association The first batch of Loyolites passed out of school in 1968, with an ISC batch. The school was running a boarding, housing out-station boys, and a Days Scholar group with boys from Trivandrum. The first semblance of an organized Old Boy’s association was started in 1978 by Jimmy Antony (’69 batch) who was the first Secretary, Joseph Jacob (’68 batch), the first President and Simon John (’68 batch), the then Treasurer. Membership was minimal and the association was in its death throes at about the late 80′s when the late Rev. Fr. Pulickal who was the then Director stepped in, took things into his hand and injected new life into the LOBA or Loyola Old Boy’s Association. From then onwards LOBA has grown from strength to strength, gaining in membership mostly under the guidance and drive of Rev. Fr. Joseph Edassery. We are now an integral part of the world wide network of Jesuit Alumni Associations all over the world, and we played a key role in hosting the Fifth National Congress of the Jesuit Alumni Associations of India, on the 7th, 8th, and 9th of September at the Loyola campus. The Past National President of the Jesuit Alumni Associations of India was our very own Alumnus Dr. Santhosh Rollands. Here’s the list of Executive committee members for the year 2012-2013. Contact any of these members to know more about LOBA and its programmes. No. Member Name Designation Contact Number Email ID 1) Manu Cyriac (2005) President 8891769289 manucyriac@gmail.com 2) Hari Shanker R (2006) Secretary 9447325561 hari@harishanker.net 3) Alex Ajith Philip (1987) Vice President 9895046326 alex.philip@gmail.com 4) Somu R (1977) Treasurer 9387711222 somur77@gmail.com 5) Jacob Mathan (1974) Joint Secretary 9847241150 jacmattvm@yahoo.com 6) Rajeev Varghese (Jr.) (2012) Joint Secretary 8089413169   ');";
